						<div class="newsRow" style="border:none;">
							
							
							<div class="rowImg"><img src="../../content/cms/uploads/small/21303.jpg"  /></div>
							<div class="rowTxt">
							
							
							
								<p class="newsHead">Breach of contract limitation period may put unnecessary burden on lenders, warns legal recoveries specialist</p>
								<p class="newsDate">Aug&nbsp;2009</p>
								<p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Professional Support Lawyer with Optima Legal, Chris Taylor, said Optima Legal was raising a string of concerns with the Ministry of Justice as part of the consultation period which ends on 31 July. He comments:</span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">“One of our main concerns is that currently there are no transitional arrangements for the proposed move from a six year to a three year limitation period.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>There could be a huge number of claims being issued within a very short space of time, to avoid being time barred. This could create a major burden for lenders and probably overwhelm the courts. </span><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">“The consultation paper also places emphasis on the limitation period restarting when a debt is acknowledged or a part payment is made. The paper refers to this as a ‘potent means’ of creditors protecting their position – we question how effective this is in practice, given that it requires the debtor’s cooperation.”</span><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Optima Legal was presenting a number of other key points to the Ministry of Justice as part of the consultation process, said Chris. These included the debate as to whether or not acknowledgements could be recorded in telephone calls, the fact that the proposals did not extend to secured debt, issues around debtor identity and location and the apparent clash with the principles of the CPR Practice Direction on Pre-Action Behaviour, which sought to avoid litigation if at all possible.</span><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">“The aim of this proposal is to create more consistency between different types of action, but we question whether that can be achieved given that it does not affect a number of different types of claims, such as those on deeds and claims by secured lenders,” said Chris. </span><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">“We are concerned that the changes may well increase, rather than reduce litigation, with proceedings likely to be pursued and then stayed to allow time to negotiate a settlement.”</span><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Optima Legal is encouraging its clients to analyse existing average times taken from original default through to the issue of court proceedings in relation to unsecured debts, to enable them to consider the likely impact of the proposed changes.</span></p></p></p></p></p></p><p> </p></p>
								
								
								<img src="../../content/cms/uploads/large/21293.jpg"  />
								
